    "media:imagetext": "International Tributes to the History of Flight\nGermanys First Airmail Flight\nAlmost singlehandedly, Hans Grade moved Germany\nThe full-color cachet shows Hans Grade on his\ninto the aviation age. The first German to earn a\nmaiden airmail flight, piloting a monoplane he de-\npilot's license, he was also the first to fly inside his\nsigned and built himself. The plane's most note-\nhomeland. His award-winning monoplane, which he\nworthy feature was the sling where the pilot sat,\ndesigned and built with a 24-horsepower, air cooled\nlocated beneath the engine and wings and behind\ntwo-stroke engine, was a major advance in German\nthe propellor.\naeronautics.\nMint Stamp: The mint stamp on this Cover was issued\nThree years later, Grade made history again — with\nby West Germany in 1978. It shows Hans Grade pivot-\nthe first semi-regular private airmail flight in Ger-\ning in the sling of his monoplane as it soars over the\nmany. On February 18, 1912 he took off from Bork, a\nGerman countryside.\nsuburb of Berlin, carrying a sack of mail. Fifteen min-\nutes later, his plane set down in Bruck, four miles\nPostmark: This Cover was postmarked in West Berlin,\naway. Despite the short distance, airmail flights be-\nGermany, near Bork, on February 18, 1984, the anni-\ntween the two towns continued until June, 1913.\nversary of the first German airmail flight.\n© Postal Commemorative Society\nPrinted in U.S.A.\n119. 056.010",
